#: ../../faq.rst:594
# c10826df52984dcea12cb1e7b1b7a39f
msgid "In |app|, you would instead use tags to mark genre and read status and then just use a simple search query like ``tag:scifi and not tag:read``. |app| even has a nice graphical interface, so you don't need to learn its search language instead you can just click on tags to include or exclude them from the search."
msgstr ""

#: ../../faq.rst:596
# 06ec8219b0a04599ad1edf5db6d74a58
msgid "To those of you that claim that you need access to the filesystem to so that you can have access to your books over the network, |app| has an excellent content server that gives you access to your calibre library over the net."
msgstr ""

#: ../../faq.rst:598
# 9153ec655aa44fb5925a38f487d60c2e
msgid "If you are worried that someday |app| will cease to be developed, leaving all your books marooned in its folder structure, explore the powerful \"Save to Disk\" feature in |app| that lets you export all your files into a folder structure of arbitrary complexity based on their metadata."
msgstr ""

#: ../../faq.rst:600
# b062516185064d85baf50502bb502219
msgid "Finally, the reason there are numbers at the end of every title folder, is for *robustness*. That number is the id number of the book record in the |app| database. The presence of the number allows you to have multiple records with the same title and author names. It is also part of what allows |app| to magically regenerate the database with all metadata if the database file gets corrupted. Given that |app|'s mission is to get you to stop storing metadata in filenames and stop using the filesystem to find things, the increased robustness afforded by the id numbers is well worth the uglier folder names."
msgstr ""

